# Internationalization (i18n) Guidelines

This project uses **vue-i18n** with 3 locales: `en`, `ko`, `vi`. Default locale is `ko`.

## Configuration

- Locale files: `src/locales/en.ts`, `src/locales/ko.ts`, `src/locales/vi.ts`
- Plugin setup: `src/plugins/i18n.ts`
- Composable: `src/composables/useI18n.ts` (wraps vue-i18n with locale persistence)
- Type: `Locale = 'en' | 'vi' | 'ko'`

## Usage in Components

```vue
<template>
  <h1>{{ t('page.title') }}</h1>
  <InputTextField
    v-model="form.name"
    name="name"
    :label="t('form.name')"
    :placeholder="t('form.namePlaceholder')"
  />
  <Button :label="t('common.save')" />
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { useI18n } from '@/composables/useI18n'

const { t } = useI18n()
</script>
```

## Rules

- **DO NOT** hardcode user-facing text in templates — use `t('key')` or `$t('key')`
- **DO NOT** use `useI18n` from `vue-i18n` directly — use `@/composables/useI18n` which adds locale persistence
- Technical attributes (`class`, `name`, `id`, `type`, `to`, `icon`) do NOT need translation
- PrimeVue prop values that display text (`label`, `placeholder`, `header`) MUST use `t()`
- When adding new text, add the translation key to ALL 3 locale files (en, ko, vi)
- Use nested keys for organization: `module.section.key` (e.g. `calendar.booking.title`)
